<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 13 日，星期日 00:01:12 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Ukraine Steps Up Campaign to Isolate Russian-Occupied Crimea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>乌克兰反攻进展缓慢，基辅旨在限制俄罗斯物资从半岛流向前线<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130773"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834742?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰试图利用西方盟国提供的远程导弹攻击克里米亚境内及周边地区，深入前线后方。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130773"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anastasiia-malenko" itemprop="url" rel="author">Anastasiia Malenko</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/isabel-coles" itemprop="url" rel="author">Isabel Coles</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 12 日下午 1:02（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-steps-up-campaign-to-isolate-russian-occupied-crimea-b11e4d01"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>周六，乌克兰瞄准了连接克里米亚和俄罗斯大陆的唯一桥梁，加强了孤立2014年被莫斯科吞并的半岛的行动。</p><p>俄罗斯任命的克里米亚领导人谢尔盖·阿克肖诺夫表示，周六早些时候，两枚乌克兰导弹在刻赤海峡上空被击落。几小时后，他说另一枚导弹在该地区被拦截。俄罗斯国防部表示，乌克兰军队<a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/the-strategic-importance-of-the-russia-controlled-land-bridge-in-ukraine-832d0728?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">试图用改进型地对空导弹袭击这座桥</a>。</p><p>俄罗斯塔斯社援引阿克肖诺夫的话说，这座桥没有受损，并补充说，桥上已放置了临时烟幕，以遮挡桥梁免受袭击。</p><p>乌克兰官员没有对此次袭击发表评论。</p><p>基辅的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tactics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-russia-d9ef32a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">目标是削弱俄罗斯在该领土上的地位</a>，并使莫斯科更难支持其在乌克兰南部的占领军。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="908" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d0587735-f4b2-487c-afa7-3aaa47c344b7-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>随着前线突破的前景变得黯淡，乌克兰试图利用西方盟国提供的远程导弹深入前线后方，对克里米亚及其周边地区进行打击。</p><p>本月早些时候，远程导弹袭击了连接克里米亚和乌克兰南部俄罗斯占领领土的两座桥梁，基辅军队<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-offers-plan-to-bypass-russias-black-sea-blockade-fcac8ef?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正在那里努力突破俄罗斯的防御工事</a>。</p><p>据军方称，通过切断进出克里米亚的必需品补给，乌克兰希望其有限的部队能够使俄罗斯控制地区的生活和军事行动变得难以为继，迫使其进行某种形式的撤退或谈判，或者允许乌克兰入侵并夺回克里米亚。分析师。</p><p>更直接的是，基辅正在努力削弱俄罗斯在该国南部的防御， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰军队正在那里努力</a>穿越俄罗斯的雷区和其他障碍。</p><p> “当前线没有取得足够的进展时，这些打击的重要性就会增加，”政府支持的智库基辅国家战略研究所的研究员米科拉·别列斯科夫说。 “一切使事情复杂化并增加时间的事情都对我们有利。”</p><p>自6月发起反攻以来，乌克兰军队已重新夺回约150平方英里的领土，但突破的希望与俄罗斯雷区、广泛的防御工事和空中力量的现实发生了冲突。</p><p>克里米亚半岛只有马萨诸塞州大小，但具有巨大的战略和象征意义。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="459" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834741?width=700&amp;height=459" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">上个月，克里米亚一处军事训练场发生爆炸。 TPX 当天图片</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：STRINGER/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>自从入侵初期占领乌克兰南部海岸的大片领土以来， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/the-strategic-importance-of-the-russia-controlled-land-bridge-in-ukraine-832d0728?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">莫斯科一直寻求利用连接俄罗斯大陆和新领土的所谓陆桥沿线的后勤路线</a>。但美国去年提供的远程火炮使该地区的大部分地区都处于乌克兰的攻击范围内。这迫使莫斯科更加依赖跨越陆桥和克里米亚之间沼泽地峡的联系。</p><p>周日，乌克兰军队发射了一连串远程导弹，目标是克里米亚和被占领的乌克兰南部之间的两条主要公路供应路线之一。琼哈尔大桥是从俄罗斯克里米亚后勤枢纽占科伊和扎波罗热地区前线最直接的路线。亨尼切斯克的一个二级过境点也遭到袭击。</p><p>据英国国防部称<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-strikes-bridge-supplying-russian-troops-56564b0b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，此前对琼哈尔大桥的袭击</a>迫使其暂时关闭，导致俄罗斯后勤车队需要至少延长 50% 的时间才能通过其他路线到达前线。俄罗斯国防部表示，6 月袭击发生后 24 小时内，俄罗斯当局就更换了一座浮桥，以表明其对战争的重要性。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834740?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">六月，受损的琼哈尔大桥连接着俄罗斯控制的乌克兰赫尔松地区和克里米亚半岛。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：弗拉基米尔·萨尔多/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>俄罗斯任命的乌克兰部分占领的赫尔松地区州长淡化了周日袭击的影响，并表示主要是民用交通受到干扰。 “这不会改变我们军队和武装部队的工作方式，”他说。</p><p>然而，军事分析人士表示，桥梁受损可能会迫使俄罗斯军事车队在克里米亚和被占领的乌克兰南部之间使用更长的路线——哪怕只是在浮桥投入运行之前。</p><p>拉祖姆科夫外交关系和国际安全项目联席主任奥列克西·梅尔尼克表示，通过阿米扬斯克附近的其他过境点，距离要远120公里，这使得俄罗斯军事车队前往前线的时间增加了约三个小时。中心，一个位于基辅的智囊团。</p><p> “物流关乎数量，但也关乎速度，”他说。</p><p>其他路线也更靠近第聂伯河西岸的乌克兰阵地——通常在炮火范围内。可以通过使用东北部较小的乡村道路来降低风险，但速度更慢，并且需要更复杂的后勤支持。</p><p>乌克兰东南部侦察连连长阿纳托利·哈琴科上尉表示，最近的袭击正在对前线产生影响。他说，后勤挑战削弱了俄罗斯在南部战线的炮兵优势。</p><p>哈尔琴科表示，除了对桥梁的袭击外，乌克兰精确的反炮兵火力也起到了帮助作用。乌克兰军队还袭击了乌克兰境内较小的俄罗斯弹药库，以避免造成重大损失。他说，被占领土上的乌克兰人正在将地点交给乌克兰军队，然后乌克兰军队就可以对他们进行打击。</p><p>研究俄罗斯军事后勤问题的五角大楼国防合同管理局前官员特伦特·特连科表示，乌克兰的袭击给俄罗斯燃料供应带来了压力。他说，俄罗斯驳船运输和铁路渡轮将成为基辅的一个重要目标。</p><p>俄罗斯当局正在努力修复刻赤海峡大桥，这是乌克兰上个月使用海军无人机入侵该大桥以来第二次袭击该大桥。克里米亚吞并后耗资40亿美元建成，是连接克里米亚与俄罗斯大陆的唯一桥梁。据克里米亚交通部称，这座桥现在对客车开放，但不对重型货车开放。不过，克里姆林宫表示，对于军事供应更为重要的桥梁铁路段仍在运营。</p><p> “后勤就是一切，从面包开始，到坦克结束，”梅尔尼克引用一战期间美国远征军司令约翰·J·潘兴将军的话说道：“士兵赢得战斗，后勤赢得战争。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——丹尼尔·迈克尔斯和詹姆斯·马森对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Anastasiia Malenko <a href="mailto:anastasiia.malenko@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（anastasiia.malenko@wsj.com）</a>和 Isabel Coles（ <a href="mailto:isabel.coles@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">isabel.coles@wsj.com</a> ） </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/8d8ed83e-2dd4-4860-bd54-92b7a7ea1ada.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 17:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-steps-up-campaign-to-isolate-Russian-占领-crimea-b11e4d01</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-steps-up-campaign-to-isolate-Russian-占领-crimea-b11e4d01<author><![CDATA[Anastasiia MalenkoIsabel Coles]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Visit by Taiwan Vice President Puts China in a Bind]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>北京的激进回应可能会重新引发与华盛顿的紧张关系，并在台湾总统选举中适得其反<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130732"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834715?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">台湾副总统赖清德定于周六晚抵达纽约。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ritchie B. Tongo/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130732"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chunhan-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">Chun Han Wong</a></span> Joyu Wang 和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/charles-hutzler" itemprop="url" rel="author">Charles Hutzler</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 12 日中午 12:21（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-visit-by-taiwan-vice-president-puts-china-in-a-bind-a275b893"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>台湾总统今年春天访问美国后，中国以为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-military-greets-return-of-taiwans-president-with-live-fire-drills-e6737c7c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">期三天的实弹军事演习</a>作为回应，并发出一系列谴责，声称对台湾拥有主权。</p><p>现在，台湾副总统赖清德将于周六晚抵达纽约，中国领导人在权衡应对措施时需要考虑更多问题。</p><p>北京多次警告美国不要允许黎智英在往返巴拉圭的途中在美国停留，并谴责这条路线具有挑衅性。在黎智英出访前几天，中国军队加大了对台湾附近空域和水域的出动力度，其官方电视台还发布了一部纪录片，片中士兵们表示愿意在攻击台湾岛时牺牲生命。</p><p>然而，台湾官员和政治分析人士表示，北京可能会出于多种原因限制其反应。</p><p>一是担心会破坏缓解与华盛顿紧张关系的微妙努力。另一个是对台湾一月份总统选举的潜在影响。黎智英是目前竞选中的领跑者，挑衅性的行动可能会提高他在台湾选民中的受欢迎程度，这些选民越来越不满中国大陆的欺凌行为。</p><p>一名台湾高级官员表示，“北京根据过去几年的经验采取的任何行动，都可能有助于赖清德得分。”他指的是过去的选举中，中国的激进行动为执政党候选人提供了支持。 “这对北京没有任何好处。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>黎智英过境之际，华盛顿和北京<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-china-poised-to-drift-further-apart-after-investment-ban-1e37427d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正试图通过尝试性地努力控制台湾、乌克兰战争、间谍活动和技术控制方面的摩擦来缓解紧张局势</a>。对于北京来说，缓和与华盛顿的紧张关系将有助于减轻对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国经济低迷的</a>外部压力，尽管中国官员也向美国同行强调，他们不会在核心利益上妥协——包括台湾与大陆统一的目标。</p><p>赖清德定于周六抵达纽约，并于第二天晚上启程前往巴拉圭，这是为期七天的访问的一部分，出席巴拉圭候任总统的就职典礼。按照以往此类访问的先例，黎智英不会前往华盛顿，但将在返回台湾的途中经停旧金山。</p><p>台湾官员过境美国（正式称为过境）是华盛顿和台北之间精心安排的一部分，目的是让台湾领导人在两国政府于 1979 年断交后在美国领土上与对方进行接触。</p><p>台湾外交部上个月表示，赖智过境的安排与以往的做法没有什么不同，不应成为中国进行挑衅的借口。</p><p>最近的民意调查显示，执政的民进党总统候选人赖智在明年接替蔡英文总统的竞选中处于领先地位，不过观察人士表示，三人竞争太不稳定，无法选出最受青睐的候选人，距离大选还有几个月的时间。一月份的选举。</p><p>在黎智英出访之前，中国官方媒体抨击黎智英是一心煽动紧张局势的分裂分子。北京认为他比蔡英文更热衷于台独。部分原因是他之前曾发表过言论，包括2017年他将自己描述为“台独”的“务实”工作者。</p><p>黎智英表示，如果当选，他不会寻求改变台湾与大陆之间的现状。在周一播出的电视采访中，黎智英在谈到他 2017 年的言论时表示，他指的是他将如何努力保护台湾的主权。 “事实是台湾不是中华人民共和国的一部分，”他说。</p><p>美国和台湾官员计划在黎智英过境美国期间对其保密。预计他将与纽约和旧金山的台湾社区成员会面。与蔡英文在三月底和四月初的停留不同，赖智不会发表公开言论，不会会见美国智库学者，也不太可能会见除处理台湾政策的官员以外的政府官员，尽管国会议员可能会到场。</p><p>黎智英一行的代表上个月前往华盛顿，部分原因是为此次访问做准备。据一位知情人士透露，美国官员传达的信息是：美国正在倾听黎智英的每一句话。</p><p>拜登政府担忧的一个原因是黎智英最近在竞选时发表的言论，称他期待“台湾总统能走进白宫”的那一天。这番言论引起了人们的关注，因为这表明赖智可能正在寻求对台湾的全面外交承认，这对北京来说是一条红线。</p><p>美国国务院没有回应置评请求。</p><p>中国军队，即中国人民解放军，几乎每天都加强了对台湾防空识别区的入侵，周日派出两打战斗机、轰炸机和其他飞机在台湾附近出动，周四又派出 33 架次。</p><p>中国国家电视台本周还开始播出纪念中国人民解放军成立 96 周年的八集纪录片系列《追梦》，其中包含台湾周边军事演习的镜头。其中包括对一名中国喷气机飞行员的采访，他说，如果真正爆发战斗，“我的战斗机将是我的最后一枚导弹”。</p><p>周五，即赖昌星启程前往美国的前一天，中国海事当局宣布在距离台湾东北约 300 英里的浙江省沿海举行为期三天的军事演习。台北国防部表示，岛内军方将密切关注此次演习。</p><p> “中国在认知战中使用的一种策略是通过夸大传播信息来放大例行演习，”台湾军方发言人孙丽芳少将在周六赖智前往纽约之前接受采访时表示。他在谈到这次演习以及中国可能做出的反应时表示，“这是为了放大对台湾进行例行演习的威胁。”</p><p>一些政治分析人士预计，中国将进一步加强在台湾附近的军事活动，以回应黎智英的访问，甚至可能重复四月份的实弹演习。</p><p>北京“不会反应过度，但他们肯定会做出反应，”新加坡南洋理工大学研究中国外交政策的助理教授迪伦·卢(Dylan Loh)表示。他表示，“虽然目前与华盛顿建立更好的关系符合北京的利益”，但这并不意味着中国领导人会在认为有必要时回避对台湾采取强硬行动。</p><p>尽管如此，分析人士表示，北京将不得不考虑过去展示军事力量是如何激起台湾人的怨恨的。 1996 年台湾总统选举之前，中国在台湾附近进行了军事演习并发射了导弹，当时的总统李登辉以 54% 的支持率获胜，他曾帮助台湾走向民主，并被视为支持台湾独立。投票。</p><p>在澳大利亚国立大学教授台湾研究的政治学家宋文蒂表示，如果中国对赖的过境反应强烈，“实际上会对北京产生适得其反的效果”。</p><p>写信给 Chun Han Wong（ <a href="mailto:chunhan.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chunhan.wong@wsj.com）</a> 、Joyu Wang（ <a href="mailto:joyu.wang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joyu.wang@wsj.com）</a>和 Charles Hutzler（ <a href="mailto:charles.hutzler@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">charles.hutzler@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 16:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-visit-by-taiwan-vice-president-puts-china-in-a-bind-a275b893</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-visit-by-taiwan-vice-president-puts-china-in-a-bind-a275b893<author><![CDATA[Chun Han WongCharles Hutzler]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>赖清德</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Pakistan Appoints Caretaker Prime Minister as Poll Timing Remains in Doubt]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一名与巴基斯坦强大军方有联系的参议员将监督下一次选举之前的时期，这次选举可能会被推迟<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130718"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834738?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">打着条纹领带的谢巴兹·谢里夫走在与国民议会成员合影前。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Waseem Khan/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130718"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/saeed-shah" itemprop="url" rel="author">赛义德·沙阿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 11:58 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-appoints-caretaker-prime-minister-as-poll-timing-remains-in-doubt-7096330f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>巴基斯坦伊斯兰堡——周六，一位因与巴基斯坦强大军方有着密切联系而闻名的参议员被任命为临时总理，旨在监督下一次选举之前的时期，但这些民意调查的时间仍不清楚。</p><p>安瓦尔·哈克·卡卡尔（Anwaar ul Haq Kakar）有商业背景，在巴基斯坦动荡的、军事主导的政治中被誉为聪明的政治操盘手。他来自西部俾路支省，该国资源丰富但最不发达的地区，与阿富汗和伊朗接壤，他是该地区一个小政党的成员。</p><p>即将离任的总理谢赫巴兹·谢里夫于 8 月 9 日<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-dissolves-parliament-as-government-grapples-with-political-instability-9151fdb2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">解散了议会</a>，为选举奠定了基础，根据宪法，选举应在 11 月初举行。谢里夫近日表示，选举将推<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-pakistani-prime-minister-imran-khan-convicted-in-corruption-case-749f405c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">迟到明年</a>。负责宣布投票日期的巴基斯坦选举委员会迄今为止对投票日期保持沉默。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="758" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834735?width=639&amp;height=758" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Anwaar ul Haq Kakar 有商业背景。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：banaras khan/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>近几个月来，巴基斯坦主要反对派领导人、前总理伊姆兰·汗及其领导的正义运动党遭到镇压，引发了人们对下一次选举的公平性的质疑。汗上周<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-pakistani-prime-minister-imran-khan-convicted-in-corruption-case-749f405c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">因腐败指控被定罪</a>，被判处三年监禁。选举委员会随后取消了他五年内竞选议会的资格。汗已对定罪提出上诉。</p><p>他的数千名支持者被拘留，记者也面临压力。</p><p>谢里夫曾表示，只有根据今年进行的新人口普查重新划定选区边界后才能举行选举，这需要时间来管理。这项任务预计会将投票至少推迟到明年二月。</p><p>临时政府的权力得到加强，使新总理能够做出经济决策，这加剧了人们对他的任期将延长的猜测。</p><p>临时总理的一项可能任务是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gulf-nations-poised-to-invest-billions-in-pakistan-as-it-seeks-infusion-of-foreign-currency-9dfbb2ad?mod=world_major_2_pos6&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">与海湾国家达成协议</a>，这些国家正在寻求在巴基斯坦投资数十亿美元。如果到三月份他仍在任，他还将面临与国际货币基金组织的新谈判，国际货币基金组织今年早些时候向巴基斯坦<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-clinches-3-billion-in-imf-rescue-lending-698e63ce?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">提供了为期九个月的救助</a>。</p><p>卡卡尔的名字是在即将离任的政府与反对派领导人就选择谁担任看守总理进行谈判后出现的。这位 52 岁的总统预计将于周一宣誓就职。</p><p>汗的政党将在这些谈判中领导反对派。但去年，他在 2022 年 4 月在议会的不信任投票中落败后，曾下令议员辞职——他错误地计算出辞职将迫使议会立即辞职。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>举行选举。他的政党对临时总理的任命没有发言权。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834736?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴基斯坦前总理伊姆兰·汗的支持者谴责他的被捕。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿里夫·阿里/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>汗的政党表示，选举应在议会解散之日起 90 天内举行。</p><p>拉贾·里亚兹·艾哈迈德(Raja Riaz Ahmad)在去年的不信任投票中脱离了汗的政党，使他成为反对派领袖。他表示，选择卡卡尔是因为他没有争议，并且给了一个较小的省份一个机会，参考俾路支省的人口规模。该地区是迄今为止面积最大但人口最少的省份——巴基斯坦在政治上由旁遮普省主导，该省拥有一半的人口。</p><p>俾路支省矿产资源丰富。这里是沙特阿拉伯正在寻求投资的巨型雷科迪克铜矿所在地，也可能是沙特炼油厂的所在地，该炼油厂将耗资高达 140 亿美元。</p><p>写信给 Saeed Shah，邮箱为<a href="mailto:saeed.shah@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">saeed.shah@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 15:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-appoints-caretaker-prime-minister-as-poll-timing-remains-in-doubt-7096330f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-appoints-caretaker-prime-minister-as-poll-timing-remains-in-doubt-7096330f<author><![CDATA[Saeed Shah]]></author><category>管理</category><category>管理层变动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>管理</category><category>管理举措</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[18 Years at Guantanamo Without Charge. Hundreds of Paintings.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>艾哈迈德·拉巴尼 (Ahmed Rabbani) 在美国反恐战争中被拘留，于二月获释。他的作品描绘了拘留中的生活：没有窗户的牢房、手腕吊着的男人、强行喂食的椅子。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823048/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="艾哈迈德·拉巴尼 (Ahmed Rabbani) 七月在巴基斯坦卡拉奇的家附近拍摄。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>艾哈迈德·拉巴尼 (Ahmed Rabbani) 七月在巴基斯坦卡拉奇的家附近拍摄。因西娅·赛义德 (Insiya Syed) 供职于《华尔街日报》<span>因西娅·赛义德 (Insiya Syed) 供职于《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117763"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117763"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/feliz-solomon" itemprop="url" rel="author">费利斯</a></span>·所罗门</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 8:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/540-days-at-cia-black-sites-18-years-at-guantanamo-without-charge-hundreds-of-paintings-now-out-in-the-world-4f121799"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>在美国反恐战争初期，美国当局拘留了艾哈迈德·拉巴尼，认为他是其他人。他们很快意识到自己的错误，但后来表示他本人为恐怖分子提供了便利。<br><br>拉巴尼否认这一点，而且他从未被指控犯罪。在关塔那摩湾待了 18.5 年后，他于 2 月在巴基斯坦走下飞机——一个自由但破碎的人。<br><br>多年的绝食和强制灌食使他无法吃大多数固体食物。 “我晚上从来、从来、从来不睡觉，”他说。 “如果我睡着了，我会立即醒来。”</p><p>他说，经历这一切，他唯一的逃避方式就是艺术。他开始在牢房内画画，日夜站在画架前，有时忘记自己在哪里，也忘记自 2002 年被拘留以来发生的事情。到获释时，他已经在画布上和碎片上创作了数百幅作品。从旧囚犯衣服或床单上撕下的织物。</p><p>艺术是现存为数不多的关塔那摩湾设施中生活的见证之一，该设施在 2001 年 9 月 11 日袭击事件发生几个月后开放<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1011739405790755840?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">，用于关押美国反恐战争中的外国嫌疑人。</a> 5 月，拉巴尼的 20 幅画作在巴基斯坦卡拉奇市的一家画廊展出。美国当局不允许从关塔那摩拿走一些描绘酷刑和痛苦的作品，但其他艺术家根据拉巴尼律师写的描述重新创作了这些作品。</p><p> “他们不仅伤害了我，还伤害了我的整个家庭，”现年 53 岁的拉巴尼在卡拉奇的家中接受视频采访时说道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="457" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819115?width=700&amp;height=457" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国于 2002 年 1 月开放关塔那摩湾拘留设施，即 2001 年 9 月 11 日袭击事件发生几个月后。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：约翰摩尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>政府审查委员会确定他不会对国家安全构成“持续的重大威胁”（释放囚犯的标准用语）后，他于 2021 年 10 月获准从关塔那摩释放。拉巴尼的律师表示，他根本不应该被拘留。他说，他的客户被巴基斯坦当局抓获，当局误认了他的身份，并将他交给美国情报官员，并悬赏 5,000 美元。</p><p> 2002年9月10日，拉巴尼被拘留时，他并不知道他的妻子怀孕了。他说，三年后，他从一封信中得知了此事，这是自被拘留以来他收到的第一封信。 2 月份返回巴基斯坦后，他第一次见到了 20 岁的儿子乔瓦德 (Jawwad)。</p><p>美国国防部没有对拉巴尼最初被拘留的情况发表评论。</p><p>拉巴尼的部分说法在 2014 年美国参议院情报委员会报告的解密摘要中得到了证实。时任委员会主席、加利福尼亚州民主党参议员黛安·范斯坦 (Dianne Feinstein) 表示，调查结果记录了“无限期秘密拘留计划和使用残酷审讯手段的行为，违反了美国法律、条约义务和我们的价值观。”</p><h3>拘留</h3><p>拉巴尼说，他被拘留时正在卡拉奇担任出租车司机。他会说三种语言——乌尔都语、阿拉伯语和英语——这使他成为外国游客的宝贵资源。他说他没有问乘客太多问题。</p><p> “我正在工作养家糊口，”他说。 “就这样。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/559a23e9-def5-45a0-be80-bb2d6f8645bc.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>他的拘留是因身份错误所致。美国情报官员认为拉巴尼是一个名叫哈桑·古尔的人，据称是基地组织领导人奥萨马·本·拉登的同伙。</p><p> “有趣的是，他否认自己是哈桑·古尔，声称哈桑·古尔是另一个人，”参议院报告中引用的中央情报局电报中提到的有关审讯的内容写道。报道称，一天之内，就确定拉巴尼确实是错误的人选。</p><p>但报道称，与他一起被捕的熟人穆罕默德·马德尼告诉审讯人员，拉巴尼本人与基地组织有联系。他向他们提供的信息导致第二天逮捕了另外 11 名男子，其中包括拉巴尼的哥哥阿卜杜勒。阿卜杜勒也于二月份被释放并返回巴基斯坦，没有受到任何指控。</p><p>拉巴尼说，他多次被转移到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-court-rules-against-poland-in-cia-rendition-case-1406193988?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">位于巴基斯坦和阿富汗的被称为“黑点”的营地</a>——中央情报局的秘密审讯设施。他说，他在那里受到酷刑，直到他告诉绑架者他认为他们想听的任何事情。大声的科技音乐随时响起。他在黑暗中站着，清醒又痛苦，感觉就像好几天了。他相信自己在地下，在一个地牢里。</p><p> “我一直没有见过太阳，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823049?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在关塔那摩湾度过了 18.5 年之后，艾哈迈德·拉巴尼 (Ahmed Rabbani) 今年 2 月在巴基斯坦走下飞机，获得了自由，但精神崩溃了。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Insiya Syed for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据参议院的报告，拉巴尼在中央情报局的拘留中度过了至少 540 天，并受到未经授权的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-WB-51296" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">“强化审讯手段”</a> 。其中包括强迫站立、寒冷的气温和注意力集中，突然用双手抓住被拘留者的衣领，并将其拉近。他说他还遭受其他虐待：剥夺睡眠、殴打、压力姿势。</p><p> 2004 年 9 月，他被戴上头罩并带上一架飞往关塔那摩的飞机。</p><h3>指控</h3><p>只有少数与拉巴尼案件相关的文件被公开。一份被拘留者简介将他描述为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/plea-bargains-are-being-discussed-for-sept-11-defendants-11647377742?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">哈立德·谢赫·穆罕默德 (Khalid Sheikh Mohammed) 和阿卜杜勒·拉希姆·纳什里 (Abd al-Rahim al-Nashiri) 的协助者，前者被指控为 9 月 11 日袭击的策划者</a>，后者被指控策划了 2000 年美国军舰科尔号的爆炸事件，两人均被被关押在关塔那摩等待军事审判。资料称，拉巴尼经营安全屋，并为基地组织成员及其家人安排旅行。</p><p>美国国防部没有对《华尔街日报》有关拉巴尼被拘留和待遇的问题做出回应。它提供了与拉巴尼有关的法律文件，包括美国政府于 2013 年向美国法院提交的一份非机密事实摘要，以证实对他的拘留。</p><p>摘要称，拉巴尼（又名巴德尔）承认参加阿富汗极端主义训练营、为极端主义高级领导人工作并帮助策划恐怖活动。据说他会见了奥萨马·本·拉登，并为基地组织和塔利班部队经营安全屋。</p><p>拉巴尼否认这一切。他说，他在遭受酷刑时做出了虚假供述。辩护律师表示，这是关塔那摩被拘留者的常见模式。</p><p>几名关塔那摩被拘留者的辩护律师托马斯·威尔纳（Thomas Wilner）说：“他们为了从他们那里获取信息而殴打人们。” “他们获得的很多情报都是错误的。”</p><h3>艺术</h3><p>在奥巴马政府的领导下，人们做出了一些努力来改善关塔那摩被拘留者的生活。律师们表示，2009年首次开设了基础课程，包括英语、计算机科学和艺术等科目。</p><p>拉巴尼从小就接触过绘画，后来选择了艺术。但由于规则太过严格，他在几次训练后就放弃了。囚犯的一只脚踝被锁在地板上。每次他们想要使用画笔或一点颜色时，老师都必须将其传递给一名警卫，后者会在交给他们之前检查它。每天一小时的课程大部分时间都花在等待材料上。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/6240b021-781d-4853-904e-0e869164fbe5.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> 2011 年左右，一位朋友说服拉巴尼，一位新老师已经扭转了这个项目，他应该回来。当他再次开始绘画时，绘画让他筋疲力尽。他说，他要求律师给他带来有关著名艺术家的 DVD，并一遍又一遍地观看了 2000 年一部关于美国抽象表现主义画家杰克逊·波洛克 (Jackson Pollock) 的传记片。</p><p>他的律师给他带来了全塑料制成的刷子。只允许使用丙烯酸涂料，因为油装在金属管中，可以制成刀具或其他工具。</p><p>拉巴尼画了他的牢房的草图，这是一个没有窗户的小房间，床边有一个厕所。其他画作再现了他被捕前的生活记忆，比如前往沙特阿拉伯的伊斯兰圣地麦加朝圣。有几张被审查的照片展示了痛苦的黑暗场景：一个男人用手腕吊在头顶的金属梁上；拉巴尼绝食期间被绑在椅子上强行喂食。</p><p> “你可以想象他们为什么不公开这些照片，”拉巴尼的律师克莱夫·斯塔福德·史密斯说。 “这不是国家安全的问题，而是国家尴尬的问题。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2b91606f-c318-40e0-94a0-c2538f382e17.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>国防部表示，所有被拘留者生产的物品都经过安全检查，以确保它们不会“危及拘留行动的安全或现任或前任美国政府人员的安全”。</p><p>斯塔福德·史密斯对每件不允许离开关塔那摩的艺术品都写了详细的描述。八人最初被禁止离开，但三人后来被释放。</p><p> “中间稍偏左的是喂食椅，看起来很像一把电椅，有七条皮革约束带，它们的带扣是敞开的——两条绑在脚踝上，两条横在大腿上，两条绑在手腕上，一条横在胸部上。斯塔福德·史密斯（Stafford Smith）对一幅画的描述中写道，这幅画描绘了拉巴尼声称在长达数年的绝食抗议期间他被痛苦地强行灌食的房间。律师将描述的标题命名为“在关塔那摩湾外出就餐”。</p><p> 2017 年底，拉巴尼是关塔那摩八位艺术家之一，他们的作品在纽约约翰·杰伊刑事司法学院展出。</p><p>关塔那摩正在慢慢拆除。共有 779 名男子曾被拘留在那里。和拉巴尼一样，大多数人最终在没有被指控犯罪的情况下被释放。</p><p> 9月11日案件中，仍有30名被拘留者，其中两人已被定罪，九人正在等待审判，罪名包括共谋、违反战争法的谋杀、劫持或危害船只或飞机以及恐怖主义。七名前囚犯承认战争罪指控并被转移出关塔那摩。九人在拘留期间死亡。</p><p>随后，美国总统巴拉克·奥巴马 (Barack Obama) 承诺关闭该设施，称其损害了美国的声誉，并每年让纳税人损失数亿美元。面对国会的反对， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-transfers-15-guantanamo-bay-detainees-1471303872?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">他选择缩小规模。</a>奥巴马的继任者唐纳德·特朗普撤销了奥巴马关闭该设施的指令。拜登政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-quietly-steps-up-effort-to-close-guantanamo-11663412402" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">重新做出了适度的努力，将更多的被拘留者从监狱转移出去</a>。</p><p>拉巴尼说，他预计自己的身体或精神都不会完全康复。</p><p> “有些事情永远无法解决，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e8504c3d-c316-4982-9491-27989aa37551.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给费利斯·所罗门 (Feliz Solomon)： <a href="mailto:feliz.solomon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">feliz.solomon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/540-days-at-cia-black-sites-18-years-at-guantanamo-without-charge-hundreds-of-paintings-now-out-in-the-world-4f121799</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/540-days-at-cia-black-sites-18-years-at-guantanamo-without-charge-hundreds-of-paintings-now-out-in-the-world-4f121799<author><![CDATA[Feliz Solomon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Espionage</category><category> Terrorism</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Ahmed Rabbani</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>espionage</category><category> terrorism</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hawaii Officials Were Warned Years Ago That Maui’s Lahaina Faced High Wildfire Risk]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> 2014 年报告的作者表示，“看到有些事情本可以做，真是令人沮丧和心碎” <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834584/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="周二，茂宜岛拉海纳旅游胜地前街的空气中弥漫着烟雾和火焰。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>周二，茂宜岛拉海纳旅游胜地前街的空气中弥漫着浓烟和火焰。艾伦·迪卡/美联社<span>艾伦·迪卡/美联社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129932"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129932"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-frosch" itemprop="url" rel="author">丹·弗罗什</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jim-carlton" itemprop="url" rel="author">吉姆·卡尔顿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 5:44（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-fire-risks-plans-government-e883f3a3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>近十年前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/maui-wildfires-recovery-efforts-continue-as-death-toll-hits-55-8ce5a88a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">毛伊岛沿海小镇拉海纳 (Lahaina)</a>本周发生一场野火，造成至少 80 人死亡，夏威夷火灾研究人员的一份报告警告称，该地区面临极高的燃烧风险。</p><p> 2020 年的另一份报告将火灾与经过的飓风所产生的风联系起来——类似于助长拉海纳大火的风。</p><p>该州电力公司多年来一直担心<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-maui-wildfires-hawaii-devastating-84651f12?&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">该地区的野火风险</a>。它甚至驾驶无人机来监测情况。</p><p>然而，地方当局在本周的灾难发生后表示，尽管他们知道夏威夷的野火变得越来越频繁，但他们并没有准备好让野火席卷拉海纳。</p><p>大火如此迅速地袭击了这个沿海城镇，让官员们措手不及，以至于紧急警报都没有响起。许多惊慌失措的居民无法通过该镇一条堵塞的高速公路逃离，如果他们能够逃脱的话，就乘船或游到安全地带。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="896" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d71d9981-beff-4069-bf15-9a9f90d1374e-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> 2014 年，与政府机构合作的非营利组织夏威夷野火管理组织制定了该地区的野火保护计划。报告警告说，拉海纳是毛伊岛最容易发生火灾的地区之一，因为它靠近干旱的草原、地形陡峭且多风。</p><p>该计划由毛伊岛和州政府官员参与，制定了一系列需要采取的缓解措施，以保护拉海纳周围地区免受火灾影响。其中包括稀疏人口稠密地区附近的植被、提高野火响应能力以及与土地所有者和公用事业公司合作，帮助降低其财产的火灾风险。</p><p>该报告的主要作者伊丽莎白·皮克特 (Elizabeth Pickett) 表示，2014 年计划是在六次以上社区会议后制定的，其中的一些建议已得到实施，例如灌木疏伐工作和对土地所有者的公共教育。但野火非营利组织联合执行董事皮克特表示，其他方面的工作，例如提高应急响应能力，却因缺乏资金、崎岖地形的后勤障碍和优先事项相互竞争而受到阻碍。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834651?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">夏威夷的记录显示，没有任何迹象表明拉海纳在野火摧毁这座历史小镇之前曾拉响过警报。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rick Bowmer/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “我们一直在砸这个房子，看到有些事情本来可以做，但我们找不到钱，真是令人沮丧和心碎，”她说。 “我们正在经历当出现滞后而每个人仍在追赶时所发生的情况。”</p><p>夏威夷州和毛伊岛县政府的代表没有回应置评请求。</p><p>夏威夷州州长乔什·格林在周四的新闻发布会上被问及为什么该州没有做好更充分的准备时表示，“我们以前从未经历过像这样影响城市的野火。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834641?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周四，夏威夷国民警卫队成员在历史悠久的夏威夷拉海纳前街行走，寻找野火幸存者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kevin Fujii/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834642?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周四，夏威夷拉海纳的一名居民在自家废墟中挖掘护照和其他重要文件。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kevin Fujii/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他说，令官员们尤其惊讶的是，本周经过夏威夷的多拉飓风引发了时速 60 英里的强风，导致火势蔓延到拉海纳的速度比紧急救援人员和居民的应对速度还要快。</p><p>他说：“当然，看到飓风及其风和信风造成附带损害（即火势蔓延），令人震惊。”</p><p>但这种风险也是众所周知的。</p><p>夏威夷大学和东西方中心的研究人员在 2020 年的一份报告中记录了夏威夷飓风过境带来的火灾危险，该报告将 2018 年毛伊岛和欧胡岛爆发的火灾与飓风巷的风联系起来。</p><p>与飓风“多拉”一样，“飓风莱恩”向南经过了这些岛屿，但引发了四场火灾——三场在西毛伊岛，一场在欧胡岛——烧黑了约 3,000 英亩的土地。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5BFF77C6-CC2B-49A1-B6EE-48407158F77E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhawaii-maui-fire-risks-plans-government-e883f3a3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">本周，夏威夷王国历史悠久的前首都拉海纳的大部分地区因野火而被摧毁。 《华尔街日报》记者艾丽西亚·A·考德威尔 (Alicia A. Caldwell) 在救援行动中前往该镇。照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>根据非营利性消防安全组织太平洋消防交易所的数据，过去十年，夏威夷平均每年有 20,000 英亩的土地被烧毁，比一个世纪前的速度增加了四倍多。</p><p>该组织表示，主要原因之一是非本地草和灌木的扩散。</p><p> 2020 年飓风报告中的研究人员表示，与莱恩有关的火灾是在以非本地草为主的地区引发的，这些草非常易燃，并且近年来激增，目前已覆盖该州四分之一的面积。</p><p>非本地草覆盖了拉海纳周围的斜坡地形。</p><p>居住在毛伊岛的前州公用事业专员詹妮弗·波特 (Jennifer Potter) 表示，从 2019 年开始，她开始听到社区成员对该岛火灾活动越来越多的担忧。同年，该州主要公用事业公司夏威夷电力公司 (Hawaiian Electric) 表示将使用无人机包括西毛伊岛在内的地区，以确定容易发生野火的公用设施线路。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a700a2c4-49c1-4f88-9630-4eb944bf956d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>文件显示，夏威夷电力公司于 2022 年向公用事业委员会提交了一项资金申请，以帮助抵消其表示需要加强全州电网（包括野火预防措施）的 1.897 亿美元资金。该请求仍在处理中。</p><p>该公用事业公司发言人没有回应置评请求。</p><p>波特说：“州内和电力行业内绝对知道火灾是毛伊岛的一个巨大的问题，甚至比其他任何岛屿都更严重。” “我认为说我们从未见过这种情况是不公平的。”</p><p>拉海纳的居民表示，就在周二火势蔓延到他们的城镇前几个小时，他们并没有看到火势即将发生。</p><p>当地时间当天上午9点左右，毛伊岛官员表示，拉海纳郊外的山火已100%得到控制。然而，到了下午三点左右，在时速 60 英里的强风的推动下，风势已经失去控制。</p><p>毛伊岛消防队长布拉德·文图拉在周四的新闻发布会上表示，大火的速度使得官员很难向居民发出危险警告。</p><p>他说：“那天的火势蔓延得如此之快，从灌木丛中起火的地方到蔓延到社区的地方，几乎不可能与发出[紧急]通知的人进行通讯。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="866" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834557?width=1260&amp;height=866" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周五，夏威夷拉海纳被野火摧毁的企业残骸。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些拉海纳居民表示，他们收到了紧急警报，但许多人没有收到。火灾导致该市的移动电话服务、电力和供水中断。</p><p>夏威夷拥有据称是世界上最大的警报系统之一，可以向人们发出各种事件的警报，包括野火和飓风。毛伊县有 80 起警报。据美联社报道，州记录并未表明拉海纳曾响起警报。</p><p> “通常会有飓风警报之类的声音。这些东西都没有发生，”凯文·坎贝尔（Kevin Campbell）说，他和怀孕的妻子塔莎（Tasha）逃离了拉海纳。</p><p>他说，当他试图说服朋友离开时，一些人认为他们离开毫无意义。出城的主干道霍诺阿皮伊拉尼单车道公路上挤满了汽车。由于先前的暴风雨导致电线断线，其中部分区域已关闭。</p><p>目击者称，一些居民和游客放弃了陷入困境的汽车，步行，另一些人则将车辆冲进大门，乘船逃离，或在海上等待火势熄灭。</p><p> “速度太快了，当我意识到时，就像一场红色火花横冲直撞的暴雨，”乔·安·林 (Jo Ann Hayashi) 说，她在拉海纳港的水中涉水数小时才逃离火焰。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ginger Adams Otis、Suryatapa Bhattacharya 和 Christine Mai-Duc 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dan Frosch <a href="mailto:dan.frosch@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（dan.frosch@wsj.com）</a>和 Jim Carlton（ <a href="mailto:Jim.Carlton@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jim.Carlton@wsj.com）</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e434a5c2-2dcb-4e4b-98a6-d89d6ec64d59.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 09:44:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-fire-risks-plans-government-e883f3a3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-fire-risks-plans-government-e883f3a3<author><![CDATA[Dan FroschJim Carlton]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>野火</category><category>野火</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>Hurricanes/Typhoons</category><category> Storms</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>hurricanes</category><category> typhoons</category><category> storms</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Scary Math Behind the World’s Safest Assets]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>华盛顿已经埋下了华尔街不能再忽视的危机的种子<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122968"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832926?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">桥水基金的雷·达利奥(Ray Dalio)今年早些时候改变了自己的观点，他表示，“现金现在非常有吸引力”。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122968"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/spencer-jakab" itemprop="url" rel="author">斯宾塞·雅卡布</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-scary-math-behind-the-worlds-safest-assets-a22069f9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>拜登政府官员用“奇怪”这个词来形容惠誉<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fitch-downgrades-u-s-credit-rating-56c73b89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">下调美国信用评级的</a>时机。</p><p>然而，我们可能会将 2023 年视为关键的一年，并将该机构的举动作为一个警钟。美联储对抗通胀的斗争放大了华盛顿几十年来的失能所造成的难以想象的财政危机的风险。因此，最有可能为这场风暴提供庇护的投资现在也恰好具有不同寻常的吸引力。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>华盛顿应采取哪些措施来避免财政危机？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>从历史上看，投资者为了持有超级安全的短期政府证券而付出了高昂的代价。例如，根据纽约大学的数据，1928年投资于三个月期国库券的100美元到去年年底仅增至2,141美元，而投资于中等等级公司债券的投资额则增至46,379美元，如果投资于股票则高达624,534美元金融学教授阿斯瓦斯·达莫达兰（Aswath Damodaran）。尤其是在金融危机之后的几年里，任何短期和安全的事情都几乎没有什么回报。</p><p>全球最大对冲基金桥水基金的创始人雷·达利奥(Ray Dalio)并未创造这个词，但他在那个时期可能与“现金就是垃圾”这句话最相关。今年早些时候，他在<a href="https://www.barrons.com/articles/stock-market-ray-dalio-cash-bonds-51675359763" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">接受 CNBC 采访</a>时改变了态度：“现金曾经是无用的。现金现在相当有吸引力。相对于债券而言，它很有吸引力。相对于股票而言，它实际上很有吸引力。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832438?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>国库券不仅比金融危机前的支付额更高，而且也比长期票据或债券更高。如果利率继续走高，后者也将遭受<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-bet-that-high-rates-will-linger-61cdaeb7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更大的账面损失</a>。而且，正如达里奥所言，泡沫般的股票估值使得 5% 以上的票据回报率变得诱人。</p><p>但现金为王还有一个更令人不安的原因：尽管它们在通货膨胀的 70 年代被称为“没收证明”，但长期国债一直是危机时期的首选资产。 10 年期国债的收益率实际上是用于对所有其他证券进行估值的无风险利率。</p><p>然而现在，随着反恐战争、全球金融危机和 Covid-19 大流行，政府的债务不断增加。低利率和美联储债券购买掩盖了压力：近期利息成本占联邦支出的比例并不高于 20 世纪 90 年代初。但财政部勉强抓住机会，通过发行更多长期票据和债券来锁定最低利率。</p><p>现在已经太晚了。国会预算办公室定期更新其长期预算预测，并表示本财年公众持有的美国债务将超过国内生产总值，而该债务的利息将相当于可自由支配的非国防支出的约四分之三。到 2031 年，这个数字将达到同样的规模。</p><p>医疗保险、社会保障，当然还有利息，在法律上都是不容谈判的。军费开支也不是真正可选的。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>难怪联邦政府被描述为“一家拥有军队的保险公司”。</p><p>然而国会预算办公室的预测实际上看起来过于乐观。尽管目前短期票据和票据的收益率超过 5%，但预计未来几年该债务支付的净利率将勉强超过 3%。不断膨胀的债务意味着假设的微小变化现在会产生重大后果。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832421?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>考虑一下大约四分之三的国债必须在五年内展期。假设您在 CBO 的预测中将平均利率上调了 1 个百分点，并保持其他数字不变。这将导致到 2033 年联邦债务增加 3.5 万亿美元。届时，仅政府的年度利息支出就将达到约 2 万亿美元。从长远来看，今年个人所得税的收入预计仅为 2.5 万亿美元。</p><p>复利可以迅速使糟糕的情况变得更糟——这种恶性循环导致投资者逃离阿根廷和俄罗斯等国家。拥有世界储备货币和允许其永远不会真正违约的印钞机使美国的情况好得多，尽管这并非没有后果。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>仅仅让利率上升到足够高的水平以吸引越来越多的世界储蓄可能会在一段时间内奏效，但不会压垮股市和房地产市场。或者美联储可能介入并购买足够的债券以降低利率，从而重新引发通货膨胀并压低债券的实际回报。</p><p>未来财政紧缩的一个更难以量化的复杂情况是，随着利息成本变得令人不安，华盛顿的回旋余地有限。救助银行、承保救生疫苗、补贴尖端技术甚至战争等事情的能力都将受到限制。一个财政紧缩的美国将是一个经济更加不稳定、国际威望下降以及最终资产吸引力下降的国家。</p><p>预测市场何时会对此产生严重担忧是很困难的——多年来对预算的批评已经引发了无数的误报。不过，就目前而言，安全地使用现金比以前更具吸引力。</p><p>写信给 Spencer Jakab： <a href="mailto:Spencer.Jakab@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Spencer.Jakab@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/642449b6-cdc9-47b1-a319-5f4da481a4d7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-scary-math-behind-the-worlds-safest-assets-a22069f9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-scary-math-behind-the-worlds-safest-assets-a22069f9<author><![CDATA[Spencer Jakab]]></author><category>华尔街日报金融市场</category><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>列</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>街上听到的</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>列</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>在街上听到</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[When Lahaina Resident Needed to Escape Fire, She Plunged Into Sea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Residents of the devastated Maui town fled in desperation <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834655/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="The town of Lahaina, Hawaii, was immersed in flames Wednesday." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The town of Lahaina, Hawaii, was immersed in flames Wednesday. Erin Hawk/REUTERS <span>Erin Hawk/REUTERS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130110"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001130110"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/christine-mai-duc" itemprop="url" rel="author">Christine Mai-Duc</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-this-lahaina-resident-needed-to-escape-the-fire-she-plunged-into-the-sea-7ac0c78f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Lahaina resident Jo Ann Hayashi couldn&#39;t bring herself to leave her four cats that had gone into hiding Tuesday afternoon. So while most of her neighbors had urged her to flee her home near the harbor hours earlier when they were told to evacuate, Hayashi stalled. She doused the outside of her apartment with a garden hose, hoping for the best.</p><p> At that time, Hayashi, a 57-year-old harbor employee, hadn&#39;t smelled any smoke or seen any flames.</p><p> “I thought it was safe,” Hayashi said. “And there was just nowhere to go.”</p><p> Just a few minutes later, she realized how much danger she was in when sparks sailed through her air-conditioning vent. She looked outside to find her neighbor&#39;s house on fire.</p><p> Within seconds, her front room was engulfed in flames, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/maui-wildfires-recovery-efforts-continue-as-death-toll-hits-55-8ce5a88a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">thick, black smoke</a> began filling her home.</p><p> “I thought, &#39;Oh, my God. Is this how I&#39;m going to die?&#39;” Hayashi said.</p><p> She fled through a backdoor and into the yard. She hoisted herself over a fence and made her way to Front Street, the town&#39;s main commercial boulevard, where she encountered her friend Phil Bailey.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-maui-wildfires-hawaii-devastating-84651f12?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Embers rained down</a> all around them against a pitch-black sky. Bailey kept patting her arms and shoulders, trying to keep the embers from igniting her clothes. “It looked like a bunch of meteors flying by, like billions of them, spinning,” she recalled.</p><p> The safest place for them to go, Bailey said, was right in front of them: the Pacific Ocean. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d9087a16-319a-4c97-8a63-975301c68f28.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> They entered the water fully clothed, and the pair stuck together and stayed close to shore. There they waited, being battered by the waves and high tide, rocks pummeling their feet, for what she guessed was six or seven hours. For much of the time, they had to dodge burning palm fronds and tree branches falling into the water.</p><p> Hayashi said the water around them grew slick with ashy muck and diesel fuel from downed boats. Occasionally, she and Bailey would stand up to warm their bodies in the hot, blowing air of the fires. They would then duck back in the water to reduce the risk of being burned. At one point, Hayashi swatted away a piece of smoldering debris as big as a softball.</p><p> For the duration, Hayashi squinted and stared at the inferno. “I&#39;d see swaying palm trees, and it gets brighter, brighter, brighter red,” she recalled. “I can&#39;t stop seeing it right now, I looked at it for so long.”</p><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-fire-risks-plans-government-e883f3a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">town burned all night</a> .</p><p> Before daybreak, exhausted and afraid of drowning, Hayashi dragged herself onto the rocky shore. She guided Bailey, who was having trouble seeing. When the sun rose, she realized the extent of his burns.</p><p> “His skin was all gone, from his shoulder to his hand,” she said.</p><p> She started looking for help, walking shoeless through what looked to her like a war zone. Little remained but rubble and ash. Her <a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/maui-wildfires-biden-declares-major-disaster-in-hawaii/1E4C7220-8609-4F03-A17C-70F3E330A2CD.html?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">street was unrecognizable</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834684?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jo Ann Hayashi and Kevin Campbell ran into each other outside a grocery store after enduring the Maui wildfires.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sarah Jones</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A couple of hours later, she finally flagged down a group of firefighters, who got them an ambulance to take them to the hospital. She got bandages and oxygen and took a shower. She had been covered in soot, and the nurses said they were surprised to see her auburn-red hair once she washed off.</p><p> “I was stupid to stay that long,” said Hayashi, who was still wondering if her cats made it out. “I can&#39;t believe I&#39;m alive.”</p><p> Bailey couldn&#39;t be reached for comment. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> One of Hayashi&#39;s neighbors, Kevin Campbell, said his community is used to violent storms. When winds kicked up Tuesday afternoon, a dozen or so neighbors and friends gathered at his home. The wildfire smoke still seemed far away, so he started up a generator, made some burgers and put on the movie “Shrek.”</p><p> “I was thinking we&#39;re going to stick it out together like we have in the past,” said Campbell, 37, who worked for a local boat-tour business. “Normally there&#39;d be like a hurricane siren or something. None of that stuff went off.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What should be done to support survivors of the Maui wildfires?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Around 5:30 pm, he rode his scooter up to the highway to get a better look, knowing the winds tend to change around sunset. His stomach turned when he saw how quickly the blaze was moving.</p><p> “The wind was just so powerful and so fast that the buildings and the trees were just like match heads next to each other,” he said. “There was no outrunning it.”</p><p> He rushed back to his fiancée, Tasha Anderson, eight months pregnant with their first child. Friends argued that it was pointless for them to leave, since the only road out of town was jammed with cars. Not long before, county officials had issued an advisory, saying those on the west side of the island should shelter in place unless ordered to evacuate.</p><p> Panicked, Campbell grabbed his wallet, his passport and a few other possessions along with his cat and dog. He threw the couple&#39;s newly installed child car seat aside to make room for a friend, and the three of them drove out through an emergency gate in their neighborhood and onto a back road, making their way to the highway. Dark smoke chased them out. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7e7cbb70-2cf1-4c93-a7cf-e44f7edbed9a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The next day, Campbell found satellite images online that showed his entire neighborhood had been leveled, including the house he and Tasha rented. They had recently painted and organized a nursery for the baby, complete with murals of a swinging monkey and neat rows of diapers, burp cloths and pacifiers.</p><p> He wasn&#39;t sure whether his landlords would be able to rebuild, and if they did, how he would make a living to support his family. Both vessels he had used for work were destroyed.</p><p> The couple have been hopping from one property to another, crashing at places owned by friends of friends or acquaintances. They don&#39;t know where they would be bringing their baby boy, whom they plan to name Kade, but they do know they want to raise him in Lahaina.</p><p> “We just get waves of sadness, thinking about what we thought was going to be our life,” Campbell said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> At around 10 pm Tuesday, Travis Miller, a photographer who lived on the north side of town, decided his only way out was by going through the smoke. He had grabbed a few possessions, his dog, Brutus, and a couple of friends on his way out of town. But his Prius&#39;s gas tank was empty, and no service stations were open.</p><p> He started to drive, and the car was puttering along—more stop than go in the midst of the gridlock. He worried they would run out of gas before they could get to safer ground. In the distance, they could see little else but headlights of other fleeing vehicles and the orange glow of flames against the night sky.</p><p> Stalled for what felt like an eternity, Miller struck up a conversation with another motorist, who told him about a canister of gas he kept on his back porch. The man gave him his address and said if he was willing to risk it, the fuel was his.</p><p> Miller exited the car, put on a headlamp and ran. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d0105037-1baa-4ec3-844a-af551d47c1f1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> When Miller arrived at the home, he tried to keep steady as he poured a few gallons of the stash into a more portable container. He could see the backlit palm trees swaying against a glowing sky. Explosions were loud and close, he said, maybe one or two blocks away. The wind-swept flames roared and hissed around him.</p><p> “Stealing gasoline from a fire,” he muttered to himself while he recorded his exit. “Genius.”</p><p> By the time he made it back to his car and his friends, traffic had lightened. They drove north, arriving at a friend&#39;s house at around 10:30 pm</p><p> The next day, Miller&#39;s landlord sent him a photo of their home, now merely a stone wall surrounded by ashes. Singed palms and bare tree trunks punctuated the landscape like giant, morbid candles.</p><p> Write to Christine Mai-Duc at <a href="mailto:christine.maiduc@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">christine.maiduc@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e434a5c2-2dcb-4e4b-98a6-d89d6ec64d59.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-this-lahaina-resident-needed-to-escape-the-fire-she-plunged-into-the-sea-7ac0c78f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-this-lahaina-resident-needed-to-escape-the-fire-she-plunged-into-the-sea-7ac0c78f<author><![CDATA[Christine Mai-Duc]]></author><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>野火</category><category>野火</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[This 60-Year-Old Soviet Rocket Launcher Fights On in Ukraine]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Grad 的使用表明该国对老式武器的依赖，并伴随着风险<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834038/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="顿涅茨克地区，乌克兰第 60 旅的成员聚集在苏联制造的“格拉德”火箭发射器周围。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>顿涅茨克地区，乌克兰第 60 旅的成员聚集在苏联制造的“格拉德”火箭发射器周围。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127859"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127859"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alistair-macdonald" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿利斯泰尔·麦克唐纳</a></span>Serhii Korovayny 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-60-year-old-soviet-rocket-launcher-fights-on-in-ukraine-c81690a9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>乌克兰德鲁日基夫卡——西方政府已向乌克兰运送了一些世界上最先进的武器，但炮台指挥官弗拉基米尔·苏希洛夫使用的是已有 60 年历史的苏联火箭发射器，该发射器已成为这场战争中双方的主要武器。</p><p>尽管价值数十亿美元的导弹、榴弹炮和其他武器被运往乌克兰，但分析人士估计，该国至少三分之二的军械库是苏联遗产。老式武器在支持乌克兰军队<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tactics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-russia-d9ef32a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">缓慢的反攻</a>方面发挥着关键作用，因为军事指挥官扣留了一些受过西方训练的部队并捐赠了坦克等武器。</p><p>很少有武器比 BM-21 Grad 更能体现这种依赖，它是苏联武器的标志，于 1963 年开始服役，可从卡车后部发射多达 40 枚非制导火箭弹。</p><p>格雷德还显示了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/band-of-barbers-judges-and-security-guards-uses-soviet-era-guns-to-repel-russian-drones-11675485324?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰依赖苏联时代装备</a>的危险。分析人士和一些运营商表示，这种老化的武器精度不高，容易出现故障，而该国的“冰雹”火箭供应量也已所剩无几。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834031?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">第 60 旅的连长弗拉基米尔·苏希洛夫 (Volodymyr Sukhilov) 称格雷德为“一位老太太”。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834029?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">苏希洛夫展示了他用来查找目标坐标的平板电脑软件。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>格拉德在乌克兰的军火库中广泛存在。美国向乌克兰派遣了38枚“希玛”现代移动火箭发射器， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/himars-transform-battle-for-ukraine-modern-warfare-11665169716?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">在战场上产生了巨大影响</a>。但根据国防情报组织 Janes 的说法，该国在发动战争时约有 260 名毕业生，而俄罗斯则有大约 500 名现役毕业生，还有更多的人在储存。</p><p>虽然毕业生的年龄带来了限制，但操作它的人仍然对他们称之为祖母和其他绰号的武器保持着感情。他们表示，它仍然可以有效地饱和俄罗斯的阵地。</p><p> “这是一位老太太，有着所有（老人的）问题，”乌克兰第 60 旅的苏希洛夫说。</p><p>该旅的六名毕业生中的一名大约 60 岁，他隐藏在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-struggles-to-retake-bakhmut-from-dogged-russian-fighters-c8945b93?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">战略城市巴赫穆特</a>附近前线村庄外的土堤和树木中。该武器经常出现机械问题，而其工作人员主要学会了修复这些问题。</p><p>苏希洛夫说：“最好问一下什么没有损坏。”</p><p>尽管如此，“Grad”（俄语中的意思是“冰雹”）仍然发挥着重要作用。</p><p>苏希洛夫说：“我们可以在短时间内向敌人发射大量火箭。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/11c3acb2-5214-4d56-a139-77058b777e70.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>第 60 旅的 Grad 操作员表示，他们几乎没有看到西方装备，因此很想拥有一辆 Himars。</p><p> Himar 和其他现代多管火箭发射器可以通过卫星导航系统将火力引导至目标，而 Grad 操作员则手动输入坐标并自行定位武器。</p><p>炮兵们表示，“格拉德”火箭炮的用途与现代火箭发射器不同。他们说，虽然新型武器可以进行精确打击，但“格拉德”导弹可以打击整个战场。</p><p> Janes 分析师苏尼尔·奈尔 (Sunil Nair) 在描述束缚敌人并为己方部队提供掩护的做法时表示：“它不是最准确的，自动化程度也不是最高的，但它对于压制火力非常有效。”</p><p> “想象 20 秒内有 40 枚火箭弹落入目标区域，”他说。</p><p>人权观察称，这种不分青红皂白的轰炸对平民来说尤其危险。该非营利组织表示，“毕业生”齐射可以击中近 10 个足球场大小的区域。</p><p> Grad 的射程可达 25 英里，仅比 Himars 的四分之一多一点。</p><p>与现代移动火箭发射器不同，Grad 无法为坐在驾驶室中的操作员提供保护，驾驶室的金属和窗户并不比当时的普通卡车厚。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834032?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">第 60 旅有 6 名毕业生可供调遣。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834035?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">迷彩网掩盖了该旅的一名毕业生。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “如果毕业生<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pivotal-mission-in-ukraines-counteroffensive-hunting-for-mines-78197558?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">击中反坦克地雷</a>，每个人都会死，”第 57 旅独立毕业生组的一名操作员说道。</p><p>尽管如此，操作员表示，在没有装甲重量的情况下，较轻的“格拉德”在潮湿的地面上的机动性比许多现代发射器更好。他们补充说，苏联车辆在没有火箭的情况下最高时速约为 50 英里，满载时最高时速可达 40 英里。</p><p>对于巴赫穆特附近的第 60 旅来说，Grad 最近被用来瞄准俄罗斯炮兵连和步兵。</p><p>在一个典型的日子里，旅指挥部通过无线电向炮台指挥官苏希洛夫提供目标并告诉他需要的火箭弹数量。苏希洛夫通过装有专门软件的平板电脑找到目标坐标，并向毕业生人员发送无线电指令。</p><p>一旦就位，武器操作员就可以在固定在车辆仪表板上的金属盒内的老式黄铜表盘上选择火箭的数量。然后炮兵打开车窗，将开关向右转动并按下红色按钮开火。</p><p>毕业生在前苏联国家及其盟国的军队中仍然无处不在。据简斯称，大约 50 个国家的武库中拥有这种武器或其变体。</p><p>分析人士称，自越南战争以来，“格拉德”几乎出现在所有武装冲突中，而该系统的火箭有时也由自制发射器发射。</p><p>乌克兰军事情报官员安德烈·切尔尼亚克表示，鉴于乌克兰自 2014 年以来一直与俄罗斯交战，所有苏联武器的弹药库存最终将耗尽。</p><p>苏联口径的子弹、火箭和炮弹的最大来源之一是俄罗斯，但这不是一个选择。切尔尼亚克表示，乌克兰正试图从其他地方补充库存。这是一个很大的问题。战略与国际研究中心国际安全项目顾问马克·坎西安表示，乌克兰大约三分之二的火炮仍然是苏联老式炮兵。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834034?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尽管格雷德有缺点，但操作员经常充满感情地谈论这种武器。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834036?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">顿涅茨克的土地上有战壕，该地区曾经历过一些最激烈的战争。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>第60旅的炮兵表示，虽然他们仍然收到火箭弹补给，但他们正在更有选择性地选择目标。他们的车辆满载。</p><p>与此同时，第 57 旅的 Grad 操作员表示，他们已经两周没有开枪了。它的管道是空的。</p><p>第 57 旅的毕业典礼建于 20 世纪 70 年代，管道上的绿色油漆剥落。工作人员给这把武器起了个昵称“巴赫马托夫”，这是一位现已调职的前同事的姓氏。</p><p> “他像爱自己的妻子一样爱那个毕业生，”一名接线员说道。他说，这位前同事仍然打电话询问火箭发射器进展如何。</p><p>操作员们交换了他们第一次发射武器时的故事，他们说这是一次难忘的经历。这种声音损害了一些人的听力。</p><p>中士。来自第 60 旅的德米特罗·西蒙年科 (Dmytro Symonenko) 少校自 2014 年俄罗斯吞并克里米亚并在乌克兰东部煽动分裂主义运动以来一直在操作 Grads。</p><p>起初他会认为他的目标是人。现在他根本不去想他们了。</p><p> “俄罗斯人不应该在这里，他们需要离开，”西蒙年科说。</p><p>西蒙年科说，当“格拉德”号发射满载火箭时，就好像身处一条龙的体内。</p><p> “我永远不会厌倦，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834037?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰炮兵部队一直在夺回俄罗斯占领的土地（包括该国东部）的战斗中寻求优势。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em><em>Oksana</em> Pyrozhok</em>对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给阿利斯泰尔·麦克唐纳 (Alistair MacDonald)： <a href="mailto:Alistair.Macdonald@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Alistair.Macdonald@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-60-year-old-soviet-rocket-launcher-fights-on-in-ukraine-c81690a9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-60-year-old-soviet-rocket-launcher-fights-on-in-ukraine-c81690a9<author><![CDATA[Alistair MacDonald]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>工业品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>武器计划</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Home Buyers Are Waiting Out the Property Slump]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>潜在购房者预计价格会下跌，从而抑制新房销售并使振兴经济的政策努力变得复杂化<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128238"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="507" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834708?width=860&amp;height=507" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">房地产市场的进一步下滑使政策制定者重振经济增长的努力变得更加复杂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/DDP/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128238"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cao-li" itemprop="url" rel="author">曹莉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 12 日上午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-home-buyers-are-waiting-out-the-property-slump-bcbf9239"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>在今年早些时候短暂的销售反弹之后，中国房地产市场再次陷入深度低迷， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/country-garden-chinas-largest-surviving-developer-sinks-into-debt-crisis-2a525173?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开发商面临更多现金流问题</a>，中国当局正在尝试更多方法来重振住房需求。</p><p>潜在的购房者预计价格会下跌，并认为如果他们静观其变，就会出现更好的交易。</p><p>中国的房地产经纪人和经济学家表示，房屋销售再次下降，因为中国公民开始期望地方政府提供更多购房补贴、开发商降价以及银行提供更便宜的抵押贷款。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834012?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>这使得情况变得更糟，因为房地产开发商迫切需要出售更多房屋以赚取现金并避免债务违约。中国最大的幸存开发商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/6098" class="">碧桂园</a>上周表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>在其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-property-giant-country-garden-sends-another-distress-signal-22b3bd64?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">公寓销售连续四个月下降</a>后，该公司遇到了流动性问题。该公司的财务困境给房地产市场带来了新的震动，这可能会进一步推迟其复苏。</p><p> “这并不是说他们不想买房。他们有购买需求，但只是在等待。”中国一家国有开发商的销售经理严松声在谈到他的客户时说道。</p><p>房地产市场的进一步下滑使北京政策制定者重振经济增长的努力变得更加复杂。中国已经在与青年失业率高、出口下降和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通货紧缩环境作斗争。</a>信用评级公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MCO" class="company-name">穆迪投资者服务</a>公司周五在一份报告中表示，“购房者对该行业日益厌恶的情绪也可能削弱政府为稳定房地产销售而采取的任何潜在支持措施的效果。”</p><p>两年来，中国的房地产市场一直处于螺旋式下降的状态。根据私营行业追踪机构中国房地产信息的数据，上个月，中国 100 家最大的房地产开发商销售了价值 490 亿美元的新房，这是三年来的最低月度销售额。与六月份和去年同期相比，销售额下降了三分之一。也比 2021 年 7 月的总数减少了 59%。</p><p> 7 月往往是中国新房销售较慢的月份，因为开发商经常试图提高 6 月的销售量，以报告更好的上半年业绩。 6月，东部城市杭州的一家开发商提出，如果人们购买建筑面积超过1000平方英尺的房屋，就会赠送2.2磅黄金——价值约7万美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834013?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>最近的下跌幅度仍然令人惊讶。碧桂园7月份合同销售同比下降60%，降幅远超前几个月。</p><p>居住在中国南部广东省珠海市的颜先生表示，尽管他的公司为其销售的房产提供了更大的折扣，但他的团队 7 月份的销售额还不到上半年月平均销售额的四分之一。</p><p>经济学家表示，购房者的观望态度令人担忧，因为这可能会延长房地产市场以及中国经济的复苏。中国也<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">陷入了通货紧缩</a>，如果消费价格下降使人们期望为一系列商品支付更少的费用，这可能会造成损害。</p><p>为了吸引购房者，房地产开发商一直在提供免费停车和家用电器等福利。房地产经纪人表示，这让人们对此类免费赠品产生了期待，一旦优惠结束，销量就会下降。</p><p>中国商业银行还大幅下调了住房贷款利率，目前平均抵押贷款利率低于中国五年期贷款优惠利率（长期债务通常挂钩的基准）。近两年国家基准也多次下调。</p><p>过去几个月，中国 70 个主要城市的新建和转售房屋平均价格有所下降，政策制定者更加明确地表达了支持房地产市场的必要性。</p><p>去年年底，中国当局取消了导致数十家房地产开发商债务违约的去杠杆化行动，并推出了刺激需求的措施，并为幸存的开发商提供充足的融资。</p><p>再加上中国在新冠疫情后重新开放以及被压抑的购买需求，导致 2023 年前几个月房屋销售回升，这对开发商以及股票和债券投资者来说是一个可喜的缓解。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="860" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832315?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> 4月份房地产市场再次开始疲软。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SCGLY" class="">法国兴业银行</a>中国经济学家魏尧表示，随着房价下跌，更多人开始意识到房地产市场仍然存在大问题<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p> “加上整体经济复苏乏力，人们对收入和就业的预期和前景降低，人们变得更加现实，所有这些担忧可能会在7月份爆发，”她说。</p><p> 7月下旬，中国最高决策机构政治局表示，是时候调整房地产政策了，并多年来首次省略了长期以来的口头禅“房子是用来住的，不是用来炒的”。全国各城市采取了应对措施，包括现金补贴和购房退税、提高购房者从银行贷款的限额，以及取消额外购房的限制。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MS" class="">摩根士丹利</a>首席中国经济学家 Robin Xing 表示，中国的年度住房需求预计在 9 至 1000 万套之间<span class="company-name-type">，</span>而 2021 年的峰值为 1400 万套，这一水平包括投机性购买。邢说，今年的销售速度低于预期的正常需求。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JLL" class="">仲量联行</a>首席中国经济学家 Bruce Pang 表示，在房地产市场出现好转之前，购房者几乎没有动力采取行动<span class="company-name-type">。</span> “跌得越多，人们就越失去信心。信心丧失得越多，人们购买的可能性就越小，”他说。</p><p>安徽省合肥市 24 岁的房地产经纪人王涛表示，他的许多客户都在等待显示市场走向的指标。 “他们告诉我，现在的价格不稳定，不知道会涨还是会跌。因此，他们宁愿保持静止来应对不断变化的环境，”他说。</p><p>写信给曹莉： <a href="mailto:li.cao@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">li.cao@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 12 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-home-buyers-are-waiting-out-the-property-slump-bcbf9239</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-home-buyers-are-waiting-out-the-property-slump-bcbf9239<author><![CDATA[Cao Li]]></author><category>华尔街日报亚洲财经</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>房屋销售/住房负担能力数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房屋销售数据</category><category>房价数据</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>购买/出售房屋</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>房屋买卖</category><category>碧桂园服务控股</category><category>6098.HK</category><category>港币:6098</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>政府援助</category><category>赠款</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>房屋销售</category><category>住房负担能力数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房屋销售数据</category><category>房价数据</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>购买</category><category>卖房子</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>房屋买卖</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Secrets of Women Who Wake Up Looking Beautiful (Hint: It’s Not a Good Night’s Sleep)]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> How splurging on in-office and at-home beauty treatments can help some women save time, simplify their morning routines—and roll out of bed looking (almost) flawless <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831813/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="MORNING GLORY Our model is professionally fresh-faced, but these treatments might help address many women’s daily hair- and skin-care woes.眼膜，29 美元，LilySilk.com；睡衣短裤，150 美元，睡衣衬衫，200 美元，The-Sleeper.com" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> MORNING GLORY Our model is professionally fresh-faced, but these treatments might help address many women&#39;s daily hair- and skin-care woes. Eye Mask, $29, LilySilk.com; Pajama Shorts, $150, Pajama Shirt, $200, The-Sleeper.com <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101463"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101463"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Amber Kallor</span> / F. Martin Ramin/The Wall Street Journal, <span class="author" itemprop="name">Hair</span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name">Makeup by Roy Liu; Talent: Cecilia De Bucourt for We Speak Models</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beauty-secrets-treatments-for-women-wake-up-looking-beautiful-555fdfac"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> <strong>“IT&#39;S HIGH-MAINTENANCE</strong> to be low-maintenance,” said Leanna Caroselli. Ahead of her September nuptials, the Boston nurse, 33, augmented her mouth with a lip flip—a nonsurgical procedure that creates a fuller-looking pout via a neuromodulator (like Botox).</p><p> Caroselli, who&#39;s also a fan of lash extensions, sees her pricey beauty services as good investments that deliver daily returns. She no longer wastes precious minutes in front of the mirror lining her lips, and wakes up feeling “more put-together.”</p><p> Whether you want to forgo foundation or tame frizzy locks, the latest in-office and at-home treatments for skin, hair, lips, lashes and brows can deliver visible results that let women do less in the long run, according to some adopters. But the luxury of rolling out of bed already looking “ready” isn&#39;t cheap. The top five minimally invasive cosmetic procedures in the US average between $389 (for laser hair removal) to $2,914 (for soft-tissue fillers) according to a 2020 American Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) report. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> &#39;It almost looks like I&#39;ve had a mini face-lift,&#39; said Shannon DeJarnette, 53. &#39; I don&#39;t have to wear as much makeup.&#39; <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p> Price hasn&#39;t deterred eager customers. Over 76% of plastic surgeons surveyed by ASPS in 2022 reported increased demand for cosmetic procedures compared with prepandemic numbers. Manhattan plastic surgeon David Shafer recently upped his clinic&#39;s exam-room count from three to 45 to accommodate an influx of patients. “We can&#39;t expand fast enough,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="875" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831826?width=700&amp;height=875" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Slip Eye Mask, $50, Bloomingdales.com; Asceno Pajama Shirt and Shorts, $247 each, MatchesFashion.com</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Every four months, Linda Descano, 63, a communications executive in Jim Thorpe, Pa., visits the salon for a strand-smoothing treatment, which she said boosts her confidence and reduces hairstyling time. “It makes me more effective [at work] because I&#39;m not worried about the image that I&#39;m projecting,” she said.</p><p> Sound appealing? Read on for ways to maximize your look while minimizing your morning routine. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> 1 | For Full Lips </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832587?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Do you despise drawing on lip-liner or find kissers filled with fillers cringy? Proponents claim the &#39;lip flip&#39; procedure creates an ideal, low-key pout.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Yordanka Poleganova</p></figcaption></figure></div><h4> SPLURGE</h4><p> So you want a plumper pout but are afraid of filler that could inflate your smackers to carp-like proportions. Consider a lip flip. The procedure is designed to make your top lip curve slightly upward, an effect that&#39;s achieved by relaxing surrounding muscles with botulinum toxin injections, said Anna Guanche, a dermatologist in Calabasas, Calif. A quick, in-office option, lip flips last about three to five months and cost between $60 and $1,000. Plus, they can negate the need for lip liner.</p><h4> SAVE</h4><p> If needles make you squeamish, try an at-home lip mask—but beware of any containing cinnamon oil or capsicum, which might irritate and swell lips. Instead, look for ingredients such as peptides, hyaluronic acid, shea butter and ceramides that promise to rejuvenate and hydrate. Lawless&#39;s popular Forget the Filler Overnight Lip-Plumping Mask ($22) contains all these and, adherents say, can give you a plusher-looking pout—at least temporarily. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> 2 | For Lush Lashes </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832586?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Do you bemoan applying mascara? Do shaky hands make eyeliner an impossibility? Lash-extensions could make eye makeup a thing of the past.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Yordanka Poleganova</p></figcaption></figure></div><h4> SPLURGE</h4><p> Since the early 20th century, women have curled their lashes by clamping them between the jaws of a metal contraption that resembles a torture device. If you&#39;re tired of this unnerving daily ritual, consider a lash lift, which is basically a “perm” for your top lashes, said Ashley Cornett, a Los Angeles makeup artist and lash specialist. During the treatment, a specialist applies a two-step keratin solution designed to gently break down the bonds of lash hairs and then sculpts them with a silicone shield or rod. The fanned-out finish can last between eight and 10 weeks. Cornett caps off the treatment with a tint to make lashes look thicker sans mascara. She charges $250 for the combined services.</p><p> Celine Yousefzadeh, 30, founder of a New York caviar company, used to curl her lashes at least five times each morning, only to have them droop a few hours later. After her lash lift, she said, she always looks like she&#39;s wearing eye makeup.</p><p> Those seeking extra drama can opt for extensions. Chito Ozawa, a lash and brow artist in Brooklyn, uses 50 to 100 individual extensions per eye, which she applies one-by-one with tweezers and glue. To negate the need for eyeliner, she suggests splurging on denser, pricier 2D extensions (two-pronged lashes). Ozawa charges between $175 and $275 for lashes and application. The finished look can last at least three weeks.</p><p> Margaret Siple, 37, a Seattle research biologist, has thin natural lashes. Steamy daily bus rides used to cause mascara meltdowns—until she got extensions. They&#39;re “a godsend,” she said.</p><h4> SAVE</h4><p> To add length at home, try Lashify&#39;s DIY lash extensions (kits start at $145). Beloved by celebrity makeup artists, these versions attach to the underside of your natural lashes and stay put for up to seven days. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> 3 | For Lustrous Locks </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832614?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Fed up with frizz—and straighteners? Devotees of shine-enhancing keratin treatments swear they make styling hair a speedy cinch.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Yordanka Poleganova</p></figcaption></figure></div><h4> SPLURGE</h4><p> Two decades ago, Descano, the communications exec, tried her first in-salon keratin treatment. Back then such fixes contained harsh, noxious chemicals that left locks poker-straight but often lifeless. Today, she relies on Cezanne—an updated professional service that uses a combination of keratin, glycolic acid and sericin (a natural protein produced by silkworms) to smooth strands and boost shine without combating natural texture. Promoted as safe for straight, wavy, curly, kinky, color-treated and relaxed hair, the treatment is popular among celebrity hairstylist Mateo Jon&#39;s “wash-and-go” clients at Virgo in Los Angeles. Adena Whitlow, 36, a lawyer in Vancouver, Canada, said it helped tame the “frizzy nightmare” she developed postpartum. The silky effects, say advocates, can last anywhere from 10 weeks to five months. Costs range from $200 to $800.</p><h4> SAVE</h4><p> DIYers should look for at-home bond-building formulas that can help revitalize damaged hair. Among the newest is Epres Bond Repair Treatment ($48), an acid-free spray. Considered safe for even chemically treated strands, this concoction combines four impossible-to-pronounce ingredients intended to repair hair and up its gloss factor. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> 4 | For Bold Brows </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832583?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Do you want to appear more refreshed? Are daily spa visits not an option? A brow lift, according to fans, could give you that &#39;I woke up rested and I&#39;m paying attention&#39; look.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Yordanka Poleganova</p></figcaption></figure></div><h4> SPLURGE</h4><p> Raising your arches by a few millimeters—the amount of elevation achievable with a chemical brow lift—might seem minuscule, but Siple, the biologist, contends it fosters a “more refreshed and bright-eyed” look. Los Angeles dermatologist Dr. Ava Shamban said the newest technique involves injecting a neuromodulator (such as Botox or Daxxify) near the bridge of the nose, into the head of each brow and directly above each arch. These pokes result in a “nice lift and pretty arch” that can last up to six months, she said. The procedure, which can cost anywhere from $500 to $2,000, can also create symmetry and reduce sagging.</p><h4> SAVE</h4><p> To articulate arches sans injections, Beverly Hills brow specialist Kristie Streicher combines a two-step keratin solution with tweezing, trimming and tinting. This quartet sets arches in an “upward, outward position” that gives a “visible lift to the entire face” for six to eight weeks, she said. At $425, the treatment is pricier than similar services, but “feeling put together at all hours of the day” is money well spent, said Carin Gerard, 64, a Montecito, Calif., artist and Streicher client. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> 5 | For Bright Eyes </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832588?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Is looking tired all the time exhausting? Does unsuccessfully attempting to hide eye bags with concealer add tedium to your beauty routine? Consider visiting an oculoplastic surgeon, just might be able to make you appear as though you regularly get a solid eight hours.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Yordanka Poleganova</p></figcaption></figure></div><h4> SPLURGE</h4><p> “I was tired of always looking tired,” said Rachel Montiel, 49. The Chicago real-estate broker&#39;s failed attempts to camouflage eye bags with concealer led her to Dr. Kami Parsa, an oculoplastic surgeon in Beverly Hills, and his signature Trifecta Lift. The three-in-one procedure typically involves a lower blepharoplasty (to recontour the fat pads), a fat transfer to the midface (to address volume loss) and skin tightening. Montiel expected to “come out looking like Frankenstein,” but the incisions are made inside the eyelid, so she has no visible scars. (If you can&#39;t make it to Beverly Hills, many oculoplastic surgeons can perform versions of the Trifecta Lift&#39;s three components.) Most patients experience mild swelling and bruising but return to work in seven to 10 days. This procedure is an investment—expect to wait between three and six months to see full results and plan to shell out upwards of $7,000. (Dr. Parsa&#39;s Trifecta Lift starts at $22,000.)</p><h4> SAVE</h4><p> Hyaluronic acid filler (like Juvéderm Volbella or Restylane Eyelight) is a comparatively budget-friendly brightening option. When injected under eyes, it can help counteract darkness caused by “hollowing” or lack of volume, said Dr. Shafer.</p><p> Lindsey Perlstein, 40, tried under-eye filler for the first time shortly after having a baby. “Instant gratification” is how she described the results. “By the time I walked out of the doctor&#39;s office, it looked like I had gone on vacation for two weeks,” said the Brooklynite, who works in content marketing. Results usually last at least eight months and procedures usually cost between $700 and $2,500. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> 6 | For Firm Skin </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832589?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Does painting on foundation slow you down? Sentient Tixel treatments negate the need for much makeup, say fans.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Yordanka Poleganova</p></figcaption></figure></div><h4> SPLURGE</h4><p> After a series of Sentient&#39;s Tixel treatments, “it almost looks like I&#39;ve had a mini face-lift,” said Shannon DeJarnette, 53, a retired nurse in Park City, Utah. “I don&#39;t have to wear as much makeup.” This noninvasive device delivers short bursts of thermal energy via a titanium plate studded with tiny spikes. Heated to 400°C and stamped across the face and neck, the tip creates micro-channels that stimulate collagen and elastin production, said Dr. Shamban. Designed to deliver a smoother, brighter and tighter visage, the device is similar to a high-powered laser but requires less post-procedure downtime (redness and scabbing typically dissipate after a few days). It&#39;s considered safe for all skin tones and can also address acne scars, fine lines and wrinkles. Most practitioners suggest three treatments, each typically between $500 and $2,000, every four to six weeks.</p><h4> SAVE</h4><p> To achieve hydration and radiance at home, seek out products that contain carbon dioxide, which promise to boost blood flow. Lumisque&#39;s CO2Lift Carboxy Gel Treatment ($93) infuses carbon dioxide with the aim of expanding blood vessels, rushing oxygen and nutrients to the skin that promote cellular regeneration. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> <em>Just Say No</em> : <em>Skip these products to avoid emulating the walking dead</em> </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831923?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Meryl Streep saves face in 1992&#39;s &#39;Death Becomes Her.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><ul class="articleList"><li><strong>Lip-Plumping Tools</strong> : Suction devices only deliver fleeting volume and can damage nerves and tissue, said Dr. Shamban.</li><li> <strong>DIY Microdermabrasion</strong> : At-home exfoliating devices can scrape and scratch skin. Reach for topical products instead, which are less likely to cause adverse reactions, said Dr. Shamban.</li><li> <strong>Permanent Eyeliner</strong> : Tattooing eyelids can cause gland problems. Plus, the skin will eventually sag, so what looks good now may not later, said Dr. Parsa.</li></ul><p> <em>The Wall Street Journal is not compensated by retailers listed in its articles as outlets for products. Listed retailers frequently are not the sole retail outlets.</em></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What makeup and beauty routines or procedures help you look your best every morning?加入下面的对话。</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
